Comment: ¬†@camilamansilo1132¬† Because most central protagonists in media don't have glasses. Needing glasses is still quietly seen as a "handicap". I mean, with all the rough-and-tumble that goes along with adventuring, anyone who wears glasses would be inclined to agree you'd be worried about losing/breaking your glasses halfway through an adventure and not being able to see anything. So to get a main protagonist who wears glasses, it's some nice validation that you don't have to restrict your adventures to those read in books and that you, too, can go on adventures without holding anyone (including yourself) back. That's why glasses representation is great to see.

¬†@Wizard608¬† Because people with poor eyesight require more representation in cinema. I get that the original commentator was joking, but this just goes to show how stupid the sacrifice of story for representation is. I wear glasses. How is seeing someone else with glasses gonna make the character more relatable to me? I'm light-skinned with black parents. A movie should be made that can show what that's like, because the amount of bullying you receive when you are unable to blend with the white or black kids is cosmic and worthy of being addressed to help those kids feel better about who they are. But we don't need a million forced movies about being light-skinned or mixed. One really good one is enough for me. So why is every movie trying to promote gay? I deliver hundreds of packages to people almost every day of the week. I can count the gay couples that I deliver to on one hand. They don't need a million movies and television shows. TL;DR: Too much of a "good thing" is a bad thing. Put storytelling before race and sexuality.

Let me make a prediction:
The "theme" so to speak will be how "You don't need magical powers to be special" and then by the end SIKE! It turns out she does have magical powers and she uses that magical power to save the house and she is the most special one of them all and everyone will stand up and clap and respect/adore her now... This of course renders the whole theme about not needing magical powers to be special completely moot.

EDIT: 
REVIEW: Ok I have now seen the movie and since I got so many replies on this comment I'll make a short no-spoiler review. It's basically a near perfect film, the music was good with a pleasant reoccurring rhythm, I'd recommend not listening to the songs before seeing the movie as they are "instrumental" in the story telling and character building. The characters were well written and although my precious prediction about the movie wasn't "completely" wrong the ending didn't undo the story or lessen the lesson at all. I'm quite happy that Disney tried some new ideas in storytelling, without using stupid things like a twist villain like they did with Frozen, they also skipped using a designated comic relief character/companion which is one of the things that usually bother me in Disney movies. I started feeling worried that she would get an animal sidekick but luckily that role is entirely occupied by the casa, which doesn't overstay its welcome. They did a good job utilizing all the characters and although I'd have loved to see more, maybe 20 minutes more, but I didn't really feel like there was anything missing and importantly the character I found was the most interesting ended up being well executed and had a good amount of screen-time. Just like a good meal shouldn't leave you unfulfilled, it did everything it needed. As an adult I enjoyed it quite a lot, and my 8yo niece liked it a lot as well. 10/10, I'm going to come back to watching this movie in the future I'm sure.

NEW PREDICTION: Yes, I have a new prediction. Because as every movie Disney have made within the past 35 years that have been good they will give it a sequel or tv-show usually not as good. The story in the sequel will revolve around how someone come to the Encanto from the outside world, of course it will be a young man (because OF COURSE the main character will need a love interest to have a conflict with). They will fight within the family again about weather or not they should open up to the outside or not and Maribel will end up leaving with the new person to see the outside. The new love interest will do something to make Maribel angry (like revealing the location of the town) and Maribel will go back to warn about it but. The super strong family member will be about to close off the path inside to the Encanto with her strength but is stopped by Mirabel and they finally make contact with the outside world and everyone is happy again. Though there won't really be any message like in the first movie, the sequel is made "just because" and many of the well written characters will be reduced to one dimensional caricatures of their original.

Comment:
Has anyone noticed the potential color symbolism with the Family Madrigal? All of the family members wear a prime color, also depending on what side of the family they're on: Pepa's family wears all yellow, and Julieta & Augustine wear blue with Luisa in indigo. Plus Isabella and Dolores are the oldest child in their families and wear slightly different colors to contrast; purple and orange respectively. Even Abuela has red. The only color not present is green, which is what Bruno's color is. 

The single exception is Mirabel, who wears a dress with the full rainbow of colors. I'll let you conclude what that represents.
Mirabel's glasses are green tho, and they help her to see. What other character serves an important role to Mirabel finding her way? Bruno.

Comment: My prediction might be a bit off, but I think the ‚Äúcan be special without magic‚Äù is a misdirection. I think the problem is more with the family than it is with the house. Thanks to the candle, the whole family grew up privileged, in a sense.  Knowing everything will be okay because their ‚ÄúCasita‚Äù and ‚Äúgifts‚Äù would keep them happy and safe. Once their house and gifts are threatened, they become concerned, but should they be concerned? They could just rebuild or to continue with life without their special gifts, just like everyone else in the village (assuming they are just normal powerless neighbors). The family seems more concerned about protecting the luxurious life they are use to. I mean the abuela even says, ‚Äú we must protect our home,‚Äù before she mentioned her family (at least, in the trailer). I also noticed in the flashback, abuela was holding three babies, where is the third one? Are they the black sheep of the family who could eventually be blamed by the family for the problem? That would mean the family was already broken if they rejected or disrespected a family member. What if Casita‚Äôs magic comes from the family? The fact, the family treats each other and others like family, but if that family aspect shifts then so would the house. If the family is arguing then Casita would reflect that by falling part. A fracture family is a broken home. Now, what is the main character‚Äôs role? She seems to be the one family member who is the closest to Casita, possibly the first to notice a problem with her lifelong friend. She does not have a gift to show off, so instead she bonds and works with the house. I‚Äôm also toying with the idea she actually is adopted and that is part of the mystery of the family and their connection to Casita. Overall, I think the message is leading toward the aspect of family rather than being special. But, that‚Äôs just a theory based off the trailer and is most likely way offüòÖ
author: @starwaIker

Comment:
Since this comment got so many replies I decided to write a spoiler-free review for the movie!

REVIEW: Ok I have now seen the movie and since I got so many replies on this comment I'll make a short no-spoiler review. It's basically a near perfect film, the music was good with a pleasant reoccurring rhythm, I'd recommend not listening to the songs before seeing the movie as they are "instrumental" in the story telling and character building. The characters were well written and although my precious prediction about the movie wasn't "completely" wrong the ending didn't undo the story or lessen the lesson at all. I'm quite happy that Disney tried some new ideas in storytelling, without using stupid things like a twist villain like they did with Frozen, they also skipped using a designated comic relief character/companion which is one of the things that usually bother me in Disney movies. I started feeling worried that she would get an animal sidekick but luckily that role is entirely occupied by the casa, which doesn't overstay its welcome. They did a good job utilizing all the characters and although I'd have loved to see more, maybe 20 minutes more, but I didn't really feel like there was anything missing and importantly the character I found was the most interesting ended up being well executed and had a good amount of screen-time. Just like a good meal shouldn't leave you unfulfilled, it did everything it needed. As an adult I enjoyed it quite a lot, and my 8yo niece liked it a lot as well. 10/10, I'm going to come back to watching this movie in the future I'm sure.

Comment:
¬†@descriptografandooocultism6437¬†  something I picked up from a site

"Any consideration of New Testament statements on same-sex acts must carefully view the social context of the Greco-Roman culture in which Paul ministered. Prostitution and pederasty (sexual relationships of adult men with boys) were the most commonly known male same-sex acts.

In I Corinthians 6:9, Paul condemns those who are¬†"effeminate"¬†and¬†"abusers of themselves with mankind,"¬†as translated in the King James version. Unfortunately, some new translations are worse, rendering these words "homosexuals." Recent scholarship unmasks the homophobia behind such mistranslations.

The first word ‚Äì¬†malakos,¬†in the Greek text-which has been translated "effeminate" or "soft," most likely refers to someone who lacks discipline or moral control. The word is used elsewhere in the New Testament but never with reference to sexuality.

The second word,¬†Arsenokoitai,¬†occurs once each in I Corinthians and I Timothy (1:10), but nowhere else in other literature of the period. It is derived from two Greek words, one meaning,¬†"males"¬†and the other¬†"beds",¬†a euphemism for sexual intercourse. Other Greek words were commonly used to describe homosexual behavior but do not appear here. The larger context of I Corinthians 6 shows Paul extremely concerned with prostitution, so it is very possible he was referring to male prostitutes. But many experts now attempting to translate these words have reached a simple conclusion: their precise meaning is uncertain.

Scripture Study Conclusion‚Ä¶No Law Against Love
The rarity with which Paul discusses any form of same-sex behavior and the ambiguity in references attributed to him make it extremely unsound to conclude any sure position in the New Testament on homosexuality, especially in the context of loving, responsible relationships. Since any arguments must be made from silence, it is much more reliable to turn to great principles of the Gospel taught by Jesus Christ and the Apostles. Love God with all your heart, and love your neighbor as yourself. Do not judge others, lest you be judged. The fruit of the Holy Spirit is love . . . against such there is no law."

Comment: I love how they‚Äôre setting up why the one to save the house has to be her. With all these magical people around the audience would question why they don‚Äôt solve the problem, but if their magic is tied to the house and the house is losing its magic then it makes sense. They‚Äôve grown accustomed to their gifts; it‚Äôs a part of them at this point, so of course the one best suited to saving the house would be the one who isn‚Äôt having to readjust how they solve problems. Though, it seems like the other members of the house aren‚Äôt being written out of the story the moment their powers are failing, which is also good. I‚Äôm glad they didn‚Äôt take that narrative shortcut, because it just wouldn‚Äôt make sense. Being without superpowers doesn‚Äôt mean they‚Äôre completely powerless; it only means they‚Äôre hindered. I hope they develop the other characters as much as I think they will because there is some serious character growth potential in that scene where the now-powerless strong lady is holding on to our protagonist on the edge of that cliff. I would love to see the family‚Äôs struggles with suddenly being powerless/without the skills they‚Äôre so proud of, then see them come into their own, learning the very same message they‚Äôve been trying to tell the protagonist: you don‚Äôt have to have powers to be special. I‚Äôd love to see a final showdown, not where our protagonist has to finish the fight alone, but instead where the family works together to help the protagonist achieve the end goal. They get their powers back, but they don‚Äôt care right away because look at what they accomplished! It was difficult and challenging and they did it! Without their powers!! They get their powers back and our protagonist stays powerless, but all of them come out with a greater sense of identity. This movie has the potential to be a masterpiece if done right

It doesn‚Äôt matter how good your idea is if it‚Äôs poorly written and developed. The execution is what makes any story good or bad. This movie is visually beautiful and the writing surprised me with the quality it‚Äôs hinting at. I‚Äôll say it again: this movie has the potential to become a masterpiece if done right. 
	I could give a more in-depth explanation of the point I was trying to get across, but I‚Äôm a bit busy at the moment so if this didn‚Äôt convey the point I meant to make very well and you‚Äôd like me to rephrase it just let me know and be patient. I was going for more of a ‚Äúthis person doesn‚Äôt realize why this thing is so cool, I have to tell them‚Äù combined with a ‚Äúthis person has a very rigid way of seeing things, maybe bluntness will make my point clear‚Äù. I admit some defensiveness at your jab did leak through, so I apologize for not responding as civil as I could. Comment:
¬†@hunterkudo9832¬† Ok so what do you guys even want??? What is this comment section?? You guys are complaining that this movie feels like it's just "the latino movie off the checklist" because the culture is very integrated with the visuals, setting and general asthetic of the movie. But then you also don't like anastasia because "it doesn't feel like a russian movie, just the story of some girl"???

If you don't want the story to focus on the culture, and you don't want the culture to be in the background of the story, then what the heck do you guys want??

In my opinion how Disney is doing this right now is pretty great. They are actually representing different cultures in their movies for once that are not just "white american" or "white european". You guys are blaming Disney for now making movies just to tick them off the checklist, but what do you expect them to do? Have the movie set in Colombia but have everyone talk with an american accent, not represent the culture at all, and make all the characters white? That would be ridiculous and everyone would complain!

At least Disney is now trying to add more diversity to their movies. Look at Moana, Coco, Luca, Raya... All those movies did an fantastic job representing their respective cultures and settings. It's very clear the people making these movies are doing their research to make sure these cultures are represented as authentically as possible. And I'm sure Encanto will be the same.

So honestly stop complaining that this is just "Disney ticking Latino off the checklist" and just enjoy that finally Disney is including different cultures on their movies.

(Also may I remind you Coco is set in Mexico, aka a latino country. So this is their second movie focusing on latino culture. So the checklist argument doesn't really apply)

Comment:
Imagine having this as a world in the next Kingdom Hearts game.

I can see this (Encanto) or Raya and the Last Dragon (depending which one Nomura and Disney wound up choosing as a world) be the most recent Disney film and animated film implemented as a world for Kingdom Hearts IV similar to how Tron: Legacy was the most recent Disney film at the time when it was implemented as a world in Dream Drop Distance and when Big Hero 6 was included as a world in Kingdom Hearts III.

However, I remain both skepticsl but also cautiously optimistic that future Disney worlds based on their most recent animated films (Zootopia, Moana, Raya, Encanto) don't go the same route that Arendelle and especially Kingdom of Corona endured in Kingdom Hearts III if they follow the film's plot.

If i'm going to be honest and blunt. I'd say Kingdom of Corona was more frustrating and disappointing than Arendelle in my unpopular opinion mostly during the world's 2nd and 3rd acts due to how Sora, Donald and Goofy stood out like a "sore thumb", removing mentioning of the golden flower, Sora and the gang never questioning Rapunzel's long hair along with witnessing Rapunzel‚Äôs magic powers through her hair, changing Flynn/Eugene's character, and especially having Sora and the gang be clueless of Mother Gothel's true colors while remained blissfully unaware about her after their first and ONLY time encountering her before Marluxia tolds them through context. Plus, Sora wouldn't shut the hell up when he calls Rapunzel's name which caused him to attract the attention of Mother Gothel qnd later Marluxia. Just watching him calling Rapunzel (the second time before Marluxia appeared) almost made me want to shut him up about to interfere the events of the movie and especially the ‚Äúworld order!‚Äù Plus Donald and Goofy did absolutely¬†NOTHING and stood idle while Sora remained unconscious thanks to Marluxia until Maximus woke him up the next day. Shame on them.

Even the world itself raised more questions than answers when compared to The Caribbean and Arendelle, which made the world feel forced and linear cause it sure doesn't look like Rapunzel's journey from the tower to the Kingdom was two days like in the film, nor do I think that Rapunzel and Flynn EVER went to the Snuggly Duckling with the Pub Thugs and the Dam when they separated from SDG from the Reaper nobodies, and I don't think that the Guards were also after Flynn as it was only just Maximus that chased him which would explain his dialogue: "The horse was enough, I don't need monsters on my trail." 

On top of that, the scene with Sora, Donald, Goofy and their first and ONLY interaction with Mother Gothel still raised Red Flags, and If I were in their shoes or be right beside them and if Gothel gave me the cold shoulder calling me "useless of no help" I too would raise an eyebrow and think to myself you know something feels of with this woman. Lastly, regardless if the world brought up the "New Seven Hearts" (as Rapunzel is one of them) and Marluxia thematically fit the world (due to the flower motif), neither Rapunzel nor Mother Gothel respectively never brought up his name again for the remainder after their first encounter of him, which made Marluxia's appearance and role in the world very pointless. At least with Monstropolis, Toy Box and San Fransokyo, the inhabitants do acknowledged the Organization XIII member (Young Xehanort, Vanitas, and Dark Riku) and not brush them off like it never happened, particularly the former world when Randall had a "teamup" with Vanitas, even Xaldin was handled much better in Beast's Castle than Marluxia. lol

While I'm not saying Arendelle is better than Corona, that's not the point, but  compared to the other KH3 Disney worlds stories I'd put Corona below The Caribbean, San Fransokyo, Olympus, Monstropolis, and Toy Box. 

Just imagine Sora & Company involved during the climax of the worlds based on¬†Wreck-It Ralph, Moana, Zootopia, Raya and the Last Dragon and/or Encanto¬†but have them be just "there" sticking like a sore thumb in the background not knowing what's going on and doing their own conflict (e.g. Fighting a Giant Heartless), while the movies characters just primarily play out like in the movie but don't acknowledged Sora and the gang until after the conflict is solved.

Comment: ¬†@signalfire15¬† The Madrigals represent the archetypes of the human psyche, which itself is represented by the house. Mirabel is the Ego, a force that thinks it is without power, yet negotiates the inner forces of the psyche. If you notice, she's the only one who communicates with the house itself, just as she acts as a mediator in her family, listening to them, and learning about their issues - this is very much what a proper ego does with our unconscious archetypes. After the house's collapse and rebuilding, she is finally gifted with her own door, which is the door to the house itself. This can be seen as psychological disintegration (ego death) and reintegration via the development of the strong ego. The original Ego was Abuela Alma, who herself is the head of the household, and at the end of the film she passes that role onto Mirabel, as she has finally realized he true power. Encanto is a film about Jung's process of individuation acted out through a magical Latin American family.

Comment:
I cannot wait to see this movie in theaters with my family.

The idea of a family having magical powers is just so "magically" cool.

It also reminds me of the concept of a children's novel I am working on called Kyle and Marina (about a selkie brother and sister from Scotland who evacuate to New Jersey to live with their grandmother, and must learn to work together and love one another to save the world), in which every mythical water creature has a special power (or 2), and the idea of the family losing their magic powers and Mirabel having to save it makes me think of my idea of the Flying Dutchman (the main antagonist) trying to steal the powers from mythical water creatures, end life and take over the world, and Kyle and Marina, along with a lot of friends having to save everyone (though Unlike Mirabel, the selkie siblings do have their own powers (Kyle can magically summon Claymore swords and Marina can make anything appear with her lovely singing).

I hope at the end of the film, Mirabel will be rewarded with her own power when she saves her family and the magic  (maybe the power of salvation for all magic).

Comment: Besides 'Tangled' and 'Moana,' I haven't watched a lot of the newer Disney films. I think I'm one of the few people that have yet to watch 'Frozen.' But this one intrigued me. The colors and the art style - tropical, vibrant flowers, et cetera - reminded me a lot of 'Moana,' which I absolutely loved. I went into it expecting that there'd be a typical villain - I initially thought it would be Bruno or even Abuela. Seeing that the film, magic and fantasy aside, was about family and the sort of complex issues that every family faces really took me by surprise. I absolutely loved the music, and it was the first Disney film that had me misty eyed since the final 'battle' in Moana, when we realize the truth of Te KƒÅ. The song Dos Oruguitas, the backstory, had me all in my feels. Wonderful movie. Maybe eventually I'll give 'Frozen' or 'Coco' a try.

Comment:
== Note to the STORY development team. ==
I wonder if this will ever be read by any of them, but here goes nothing. Suffice to say there are spoilers regarding the ending, so, be warned...

About that last scene, after the house is reconstructed and Mirabel receives a door knob ready to start a new chapter for the whole family. Well, if we take into consideration the door itself shows the entire family drawn on it, so it just doesn't feel right for Mirabel to look into the door knob's reflection and answer "I see myself" when asked "What do you see in there?" No. Instead, I would have taken a different approach, regarding the unity of the family towards a fresh new chapter: 

The polished door knob is clearly concave, which means the golden reflection would produce a wide angle lens effect when looked upon its mirrowed reflection, correct? Surfaces like that provide room for a huge amount of information to be squeezed together. When asked "What do you see?", here the camera could have shown the REFLECTION instead and revealing not only Mirabel's figure in the center, but the presence of all the other family members around her, as the door knob clearly ALLOWS for a spherical concave reflection that fits everybody together. It is concave, after all, not flat.

Mirabel's BETTER answer would then be "I see everyone", then attaching the door knob and thus lighting up that beautiful drawing of the family united we see on the door. It just doesn't make any sense regarding the PLOT to have an egoistical answer like "I see myself" when the door clearly shows the opposite. After all, the whole idea of the movie is to bring the family together at the end.

Anyways. I hope this helped.

Comment: As a Colombian, I can't help but feel that "Encanto" fell short of truly representing our rich and diverse culture. While the film includes some Colombian elements like jugo de lulo, ajiaco, and pandebonos, these felt more like obligatory nods rather than a deep exploration of our heritage. The setting, inspired by the Cocora Valley in the Andes, paradoxically features the sombrero vueltiao, a hat specific to the Caribbean region, which is a glaring cultural mismatch for anyone familiar with our geography. Moreover, the decision to have a Mexican composer and a Puerto Rican songwriter at the helm of the music, while they are undoubtedly talented, was a missed opportunity to showcase the wealth of musical talent that Colombia has to offer. The film's production during the pandemic might have contributed to these issues, but it doesn't change the fact that "Encanto" seems to cater more to a pan-Latin American audience, rather than providing an authentic Colombian narrative. It's disheartening to see a missed opportunity where there could have been an enriching portrayal of the unique tapestry that is Colombia, beyond the surface-level representations that we ended up with.

Comment:
Encanto: James' Huge World Adventure


ENCANTO tells the tale of an extraordinary family, the Madrigals, who live hidden in the mountains of Colombia, in a magical house, in a vibrant town, in a wondrous, charmed place called an Encanto and a red steam engine; James, who's going to have his world adventure of his own to find his lost friend; Thomas. The magic of the Encanto has blessed every child in the family with a unique gift from super strength to the power to heal-every child except one, Mirabel. But when she discovers that the magic surrounding the Encanto is in danger, Mirabel decides that she, the only ordinary Madrigal, teams up with James, and might just be her exceptional family's last hope.

Comment:
after watching the cartoon causes mixed feelings: admiration and disappointment.
admiration: the graphics are at the highest level, the full study of each character is felt, their facial expressions are alive and this allows the viewer to feel the world of Encanto, amazing!!!
But, a disclaimer:
the plot is much simpler than past Disney works, with every cartoon Disney proves that the "plain and simple" policy is attractive to the company. I also want to emphasize that the child's thinking is formed thanks to the subconscious, and if everything is simple and the child does not think, but only consume, it is not a fact that he will be able to create something in the future - to create. as a result we get the consumer) Also, the policy towards men is not clear "I do not believe that I am saying this" there is not a single male character that would stand out from the rest. the concept of equal rights is very vague in this cartoon. if he has a powerful magical ability, then he is hysterical, if he is beautiful, then he is stupid. By the way, remember the first appearance of Father Mirabelle "I hope you understand." in fact, if you remove all the male characters, then nothing will change, the lines are secondary.
To these messages, I want to emphasize the importance of equality, children need to be correctly explained from childhood that all sexes are equal and they need to be respected
Ultimately, I recommend watching this cartoon.

Comment: Since it was set in Columbia, then it was NECESSARY for the Columbian representation to be forced. As to the characters being realistic, they were actually metaphors related to actual Hispanic families, so I don't know how it's possible to get more realistic than that unless you're meaning the cartoon style, but in that case, we'd have a different view on what makes a character. As to the plot holes, I didn't see any and it would've been better if you had explained that instead of assuming that everyone can see the plot holes. As to the songs, well that's your opinion, so I've got nothing on you for that. We like what we like, but if so many people related to the characters, you can't call them unrealistic. They were simply not relatable to you and probably because you're not Hispanic
author: @elisakrivas

Comment: ¬†@elisakrivas¬† Yes, but why Colombia? They could've picked any other country too, right? The characters felt unrealistic to me because instead of feeling remorseful for their actions towards Bruno, they just sing a musical number and hug it out. Songs and hugs don't fix everything. And I didn't like Encanto's message either. Toxic and emotionally abusive family members DO NOT deserve forgiveness. No matter what this movie says. As for the plot holes, why didn't Dolores hear Mirabel going into Bruno's room at night? Why didn't she tell anyone about Bruno's whereabouts? If Mirabel's mom can heal whatever ails you, why didn't she fix Mirabel's eyesight, or Augustine's too, for that matter? Why didn't Isabella want to marry Mariano? Wouldn't it make more sense if Dolores proposed to him instead? Why didn't Mirabel get a gift? Why does the town hate Bruno so much? These are all the plot holes I could find.
author: @kineshashekhar1853

Comment:
¬†@kineshashekhar1853¬† a fact is nobody deserves forgiveness, forgiveness is GIVEN (hence, forGIVEness). A gift isn't a merit. It's done out of love and kindness, nothing more. It's okay to forgive even the worst of people. I must blatantly disagree with your thoughts on that. As to everything else:

Why not Columbia? Columbia is perceived negatively in media and Hispanics are a bit tired of solely Mexican representation when most of us are not Mexican. 

This is a Disney movie full of deep topics, depression, abuse, trauma, and therapy for real Hispanics. Why would a movie like that, especially one for kids, end realistically? For me, as a Latina who had been through this sort of generational trauma as well as actual abuse, this movie is extremely therapeutic and helpful in healing. I can honestly say I would've despised the movie if the ending were realistic because it would've shown me the trauma and abuse I went through and then ended with a, "well that's it, life sucks, doesn't it? Time to go commit suicide now," but Disney movies are meant to be more uplifting. That's why this movie had a healing effect because it tells victims and survivors to face their pain head on, accept it, embrace it, feel it, and then heal from it, and move on. Forgiveness is vital for this. Holding on to that bitterness does not help. Speaking from experience. Is that ending realistic? No, but it is helpful, which is really all that matters in the great scheme of things. 

Why does it matter whether Mariano or Dolores proposes? It's culturally accepted that men propose to women and we don't really know the time era this was set in, except that soldiers still rode horses. 

Why didn't Isabella like Mariano? She didn't think he was that smart. I thought this was obvious. Also, let's face it, we are all free to like whoever we like and we really don't need a valid reason for it. That's just life.

As to all the other "holes" you found, some are common sense if you understand basic psychology or abuse victims and other points you brought up were addressed by the actual creators of Encanto. Regardless, even though some take a while to explain, I doubt you'll go look up this completely available everywhere online information, so I'll just explain it all separately point by point.
author: @elisakrivas

Comment:
¬†@kineshashekhar1853¬† why didn't Dolores hear Mirabel go see Bruno or, in fact, why didn't she hear Bruno?

Fun fact: she did hear it all. She says this at the end on the movie as well as during the Bruno song itself. So, no one can answer why someone didn't hear something that they did, in fact, hear and it's proven throughout the movie.
author: @elisakrivas

Comment:
¬†@kineshashekhar1853¬† Why didn't Dolores say anything about Bruno?

Here's why:

Dolores: Hey, Mam√°, you know T√≠o Bruno is living in the walls, right?
Result #1: hurricane and everybody dies because Pepa had a panick attack
Result #2: Bruno feels his privacy is violated because CLEARLY he wanted to remain a secret and felt like a burden to his family, so Dolores would've hurt Bruno
Result #3: Abuela Alma and the rest of the family would just believe that he didn't want to live with the family because he hated them and, as Alma states hey beliefs, "Bruno didn't care about this family!" They would just isolate him again and he'd feel like he'd have nowhere to go because Dolores would rat him out again. 

Understanding these concepts is simple when you understand psychology and abuse.

Why would Dolores care about Bruno, his feelings, and what happens to him? Because she clearly loves her uncle and wants to respect his much needed space from his toxic family. In the Bruno song, she is the only one to show Bruno empathy. I'm sure she also doesn't want to stress her mom out either. In addition to all this, she's got nothing to gain from telling anyone where Bruno is.

Many people then question why Dolores didn't mind hurting Mirabel by telling her secret at the dining table. That's a different scenario in which she had excellent reasons to worry and gossip both for family concern and safety as well as personal gain. If you were told that someone was going to destroy your house and you and your family lived in that house, wouldn't you want to warn your family about the danger? Common sense! In addition, she had some selfish gain as well, to ruin the proposal and give her another chance with the man of her dreams. There's no holes in this
author: @elisakrivas

Fear is turned to anger, hatred, and distain, which leads to stereotypes, stigma, and continuation of hatred. Comment: I‚Äôm not saying you‚Äôre wrong, but unlike Warner Bros (which in more recent years has been horrible in their actions in general and has failure after failure), as much as Disney really does suck as a company, not everything Disney does is bad. This story also has nothing to do with LGBTQ+ and is actually pretty accurate to Latin culture (I am also Hispanic, but not Mexican, so it‚Äôs nice to have a representation of a different Hispanic culture). Don‚Äôt hate on individual art works because you don‚Äôt like a company. Unless the individual artwork would be something to hate on, such as Aquaman and its sequel. If a company has gone completely bad, then sure, hate on it, but every company, especially corporate companies, has corruption, even if they do good works, actions, or even donations for good causes. I hate Disney for various reasons, and not just because of what they did to Johnny (although that was horrible too), but I still acknowledge that Disney has also done a lot of good. This movie took a team of people who did research and a cast of Hispanics. It relates to so many people and highlights peoples‚Äô trauma, healing millions of people who needed to face their generational traumatic past. Including myself. For many of us, it‚Äôs become a therapy. Anything that causes positive change or helps people is not worth degrading. Don‚Äôt insult this one movie because the company that made it is corrupt. If the actual movie had something about it that was corrupt, then I could understand the hate, but otherwise, leave it alone. If you‚Äôve never seen Encanto, I highly recommend it, even if you‚Äôre not a Disney fan. Topics in there include abuse, trauma, generational trauma, culture, family dynamics, family relationships, a variety of perceptions that many therapists work with, and even family drama. The movie is a masterpiece and, for once, Disney didn‚Äôt shy away from difficult topics in a kid movie.
